<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="36" pageId="5" pageNumber="34" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[139,1161,378,617]" pageId="5" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[179,289,378,402]" pageId="5" pageNumber="34">Diagnosis</emphasis>
(male). Recognition. In the key to the males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1856" box="[811,922,379,403]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[811,922,379,403]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="34">Megaselia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the British Isles (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney" box="[147,287,409,433]" firstAuthor="Disney" pageId="5" pageNumber="34" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref4577" refString="DISNEY R. H. L. 1989. Scuttle Flies - Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insec ts 10 (8): 1 - 155. ISBN 0 901546 74 7." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 139, but its hyopygium clearly differs from both options. Six additional species run to the same couplet but the hypopygia of all differ as well as in other details such as the mesopleuron having a bristle as well as hairs and/or a longer costal index and/or more numerous axillary bristles, etc. In the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmitz &amp; Delage" box="[797,1085,501,525]" firstAuthor="Schmitz" pageId="5" pageNumber="34" pagination="638 - 664" refId="ref4849" refString="SCHMITZ H. &amp; DELAGE, A. 1974. Phoridae. In: Lindner E (ed.), Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region 4 (33) (Lieferung 301): 638 - 664. Stuttgart, E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung." type="journal article" year="1974">Schmitz &amp; Delage (1974)</bibRefCitation>
to the Palaearctic species of Abteilung V it runs to couplet 15, but the hypopygia differ. In 
<bibRefCitation author="Borgmeier's" firstAuthor="Borgmeier's" pageId="5" pageNumber="34" pagination="257 - 416" refId="ref4427" refString="BORGMEIER T. 1964. Revision of the North American Phorid flies. Part II. The species of the genus Megaselia, subgenus Aphiochaeta (Diptera, Phoridae). Studia Entomologica, Petropolis 7: 257 - 416." type="journal article" year="1964">Borgmeier’s (1964)</bibRefCitation>
key to Nearctic species of Group IV it runs to couplet 20 lead 1, but its hypopygium is different; and likewise for the rest of the world fauna.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252447" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6252447" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252447/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="34" startId="5.[140,177,1622,1641]" targetBox="[146,1152,642,1592]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[140,1160,1622,1666]" pageId="5" pageNumber="34">
